t-align:left;\" | [[Tallapoosa County, Alabama|Tallapoosa]]\n|30\n|41,616\n|72\n|716.5\n|58\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]]\n|48\n|194,656\n|25\n|1,321.8\n|147\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Walker County, Alabama|Walker]]\n|49\n|67,023\n|73\n|791.2\n|85\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Washington County, Alabama|Washington]]\n|5\n|17,581\n|28\n|1,080.2\n|16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Wilcox County, Alabama|Wilcox]]\n|12\n|11,670\n|103\n|888.5\n|13\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Winston County, Alabama|Winston]]\n|3\n|24,484\n|12\n|613.0\n|40\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |1,812\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Alabama]]\n[[Category:2020 in Alabama|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Health in Alabama]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Alabama, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alabama\n| map1            = File:COVID-19 Cases by counties of Alabama 03-22-2020.png\n| legend1         = {{legend|#EC1C24|Confirmed cases}}\n '''''Map last updated on March 22, 2020 at 5:20 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]'''''\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Montgomery County, Alabama|Montgomery County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 13, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 1,796 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alabamapublichealth.gov/infectiousdiseases/2019-coronavirus.html|title=Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 31\n| website         = [https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/infectiousdiseases/2019-coronavirus.html Alabama Department of Public Health]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alabama]] in March 2020. As of April 5, 2020, the Alabama Department of Public Health confirmed 1,796 positive cases of [[COVID-19]] in the state.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/infectiousdiseases/2019-coronavirus.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/17/adph-update-public-covid-am/|title=Alabama coronavirus cases climb to 39; Closures ordered in some counties|author=WSFA Staff|website=WSFA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alabama medical cases chart}}\n\n{{Bar chart\n| float       = right\n| title         = New Cases Reported Per Day in Alabama\n| caption       = '''Source''':  data in the chart, \"COVID-19 <br/> \ncases in Alabama, United States,\" shown <br/>\nabove.\n| label_type    = Date\n| data_type     = New Cases\n| data_max    = 300\n| label1   = 2020-03-16\n| data1    = 7\n| color1   = cyan\n| label2   = 2020-03-17\n| data2    = 10\n| color2   = cyan\n| label3   = 2020-03-18\n| data3    = 12\n| color3   = cyan\n| label4   = 2020-03-19\n| data4    = 27\n| color4   = cyan\n| label5   = 2020-03-20\n| data5    = 28\n| color5   = cyan\n| label6   = 2020-03-21\n| data6    = 25\n| color6   = cyan\n| label7   = 2020-03-22\n| data7    = 26\n| color7   = cyan\n| label8   = 2020-03-23\n| data8    = 39\n| color8   = cyan\n| label9   = 2020-03-24\n| data9    = 46\n| color9   = cyan\n| label10   = 2020-03-25\n| data10    = 144\n| color10   = cyan\n| label11   = 2020-03-26\n| data11    = 144\n| color11   = cyan\n| label12   = 2020-03-27\n| data12    = 109\n| color12   = cyan\n| label13   = 2020-03-28\n| data13    = 81\n| color13   = cyan\n| label14   = 2020-03-29\n| data14    = 107\n| color14   = cyan\n| label15   = 2020-03-30\n| data15    = 80\n| color15   = cyan\n| label16   = 2020-03-31\n| data16    = 72\n| color16   = cyan\n| label17   = 2020-04-01\n| data17    = 105\n| color17   = cyan\n| label18   = 2020-04-02\n| data18    = 167\n| color18   = cyan\n| label19   = 2020-04-03\n| data19    = 203\n| color19   = cyan\n| label20   = 2020-04-04\n| data20    = 115\n| color20   = cyan\n| label21   = 2020-04-05\n| data21    = 243\n| color21   = cyan\n}}\n\n=== January 2020&ndash;February 2020 ===\n\nOn January 22, the [[Alabama Department of Public Health]] asked healthcare providers to conduct screening of patients seeking care for influenza-like illnesses with travel to Wuhan, China, and said the \"CDC continues to believe the risk of 2019-nCoV to the American public at large remains low at this time.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/01/22b.html|title=ADPH joins with CDC and other state health departments to prevent the spread of new coronavirus {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, the Alabama Department of Public Health asked travelers to mainland China who returned to the United States on or after January 22, 2020 to Infectious Diseases and Outbreaks Division as soon as they arrive in Alabama.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/02/04.html|title=ADPH initiates monitoring activities for travelers from mainland China for 2019-nCoV {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On the same day, [[Kay Ivey|Alabama Governor Kay Ivey]] delivered the \"State of the State\" address, with no mention of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alabamanews.net/2020/02/04/governor-ivey-delivers-2020-state-of-the-state-address/|title=Governor Ivey Delivers 2020 State of the State Address|date=2020-02-05|website=Alabama News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite speech |url=https://www.alabamanews.net/content/uploads/2020/02/Embargoed-SOTS-2020.pdf |last=Ivey |first=Kay |author-link=Kay Ivey |location=Alabama State Capitol |date=2020-02-04 |access-date=2020-03-24 |title=2020 State of the State Address}}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS) announced that an Anniston, Alabama facility would be used as a COVID-19 quarantine center.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.waff.com/2020/02/23/anniston-city-leaders-blindsided-by-plan-use-local-fema-facility-part-coronavirus-quarantine/ |title=Anniston city leaders blindsided by plan to use local FEMA facility as part of Coronavirus quarantine |last=Staff |first=WBRC |website=WAFF |language=en-US |access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On February 23, Governor Ivey announced cancellation of the HHS plans to use an Anniston, Alabama facility as a quarantine center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wkrg.com/health/coronavirus/governor-kay-ivey-president-trump-cancels-plans-for-cruise-ship-coronavirus-quarantine-in-alabama/|title=Governor Kay Ivey: President Trump cancels plans for cruise ship coronavirus quarantine in Alabama|date=2020-02-23|website=WKRG News 5|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, the Alabama Department of Public Health recommended individuals protect themselves from COVID-19 by getting a flu shot and \"other normal precautions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/02/28.html|title=ADPH recommends flu shot and other normal precautions amid COVID-19 outbreak {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n\n==== March 2\u20136 ====\nOn March 2, the Alabama Department of Public Health advised individuals to \"wash your hands frequently, avoid touching your face, cover coughs and sneezes, stay home when you are ill, and practice social distancing strategies\". ADPH also asks universities and colleges to implement plans to mitigate spread of disease on their campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/03/02.html|title=Alabama is prepared for COVID-19; supports CDC recommendations for returning travelers {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 5, the Alabama Department of Public Health announced state laboratory capability of COVID-19 testing and criteria for testing eligibility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/03/06.html|title=ADPH state laboratory now tests for novel coronavirus COVID-19 {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> March 6 saw the formation of Alabama Coronavirus task force.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtok.com/content/news/Ivey-establishes-Coronavirus-Task-Force-568560511.html|title=Ivey establishes Coronavirus Task Force|last=WTOK|website=www.wtok.com|language=english|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==== March 12\u201316 ====\nOn March 12, all schools were closed from March 18 until April 6.<ref>[https://www.al.com/news/f80301-coronavirus-covid19-in-alabama-what-you-need-to-know-now.html Live updates: K-12 schools to close; 6 coronavirus cases in Alabama] AL.com</ref> Governor Ivey said: \"There\u2019s no need to panic or close huge events right now.\" Urges Alabamans to wash hands, cover coughts, and fist bump instead of shaking hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.waaytv.com/content/news/Theres-no-need-to-panic-Gov-Kay-Ivey-urges-coronavirus-calm-for-Alabamians-568764211.html|title='There's no need to panic:' Gov. Kay Ivey urges coronavirus calm for Alabamians|website=WAAY News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 13, Governor Ivey declared a state of emergency due to the spread of the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dothanfirst.com/news/watch-live-gov-ivey-expected-to-make-major-coronavirus-announcement/|title=State of emergency declared in Alabama, 1 coronavirus case confirmed in Jefferson County|date=2020-03-13|website=WDHN - DothanFirst.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 15, Gov. Ivey authorized state agency directors to implement work from home and flexible work schedules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/GovernorKayIvey/status/1239311957561393153|title=Effective on Monday, March 16, I will be authorizing agency directors to implement telework, flexible work schedules and practice social distancing for the next three weeks. #alpolitics #COVID19|last=Ivey|first=Governor Kay|date=2020-03-15|website=@GovernorKayIvey|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 16, the Alabama Department of Public Health announced recommendations concerning public gatherings, food establishment and other retail venues, and businesses, including no mass gatherings of 50+ persons or more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/03/16.html|title=ADPH offers new recommendations regarding public gatherings in response to COVID-19 {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==== March 18\u201320 ====\nOn March 18, statewide health order prohibited all non-work related gatherings of 25+ persons or any non-work related gatherings that cannot maintain consistent six-foot spacing between people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/03/19/governor-ivey-issues-statewide-health-order/|title=Governor Ivey, ADPH issue statewide health order|last=Staff|first=WBRC|website=www.wbrc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The Alabama Department of Public Health confirmed that the number of positive coronavirus cases had increased to 78 in the state.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public and private beaches closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/gov-kay-ivey-closes-alabama-beaches-because-of-coronavirus.html|title=Ivey closes all Alabama beaches both public and private because of coronavirus|date=2020-03-19|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Governor Ivey announced that Alabama's Primary Runoff Election would be postponed to July 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.alabama.gov/newsroom/2020/03/governor-ivey-announces-new-primary-runoff-election-date/|title=Governor Ivey Announces New Primary Runoff Election Date|date=2020-03-18|website=Office of the Governor of Alabama|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the total number of confirmed cases has surpassed 100, to 106.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox10tv.com/news/coronavirus/alabama-now-up-to-confirmed-covid--cases/article_e80de830-6abd-11ea-9dfd-9b089de280c3.html|title=Alabama now up to 106 confirmed COVID-19 cases|website=FOX10 News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Gov. Ivey authorizes up to 100 Alabama National Guard members to assist with response \"if it becomes necessary.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc3340.com/news/local/governor-ivey-authorizes-national-guard-to-help-with-covid-19-if-necessary|title=Governor Ivey authorizes National Guard to help with COVID-19 operations if necessary|last=Helean|first=Jack|date=2020-03-20|website=WBMA|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The Alabama Department of Public Health refined guidance on public gatherings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/news/2020/03/20.html|title=State Health Officer issues amended health order suspending public gatherings {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> [[Auburn University]] announced postponement of its spring graduation ceremony and a move to fully online classes after spring break.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs42.com/news/health/coronavirus/auburn-university-postpones-spring-graduation-ceremony-resuming-online-only-classes-after-break/|title=Auburn University postpones spring graduation ceremony, resuming online-only classes after break|date=2020-03-20|website=CBS 42|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==== March 22\u201325 ====\nOn March 22, the total number of confirmed cases reached 150.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} On March 24, [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] issued a stay-at-home order (as a 24-hour curfew) effective March 24 to April 3.<ref>{{cite news|title=City of Birmingham under Shelter in Place in order|publisher=[[WBRC]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/24/birminghams-mayor-proposes-ordinance-shelter-place-during-coronavirus-outbreak/}}</ref> On March 25, the total number of confirmed cases jumped to 386 from 219. The number of people tested is 2,812.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/infectiousdiseases/2019-coronavirus.html|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=Alabama Department of Public Health|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The first death in the state is reported in Jackson County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/national/us/story/2020/mar/25/alabama-reports-first-coronavirus-death-cases-near-400/519125/|title=Alabama reports first coronavirus death as cases near 400-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] city mayor [[Walt Maddox]] issued a city-wide curfew, lasting from 10:00&nbsp;p.m. until 5:00&nbsp;a.m. each day, effective March 27 to April 3.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tuscaloosa Mayor Walt Maddox issues curfew for city|url=https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/25/tuscaloosa-mayor-walt-maddox-issues-curfew-city/|publisher=[[WBRC]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 26\u201327 ====\nAt a March 26 press conference, Governor Ivey said that she would not issue a shelter-in-place order, saying \"... we are not Louisiana, we are not New York state, we are not California ... right now is not the time to order people to shelter in place.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/2020/03/26/coronavirus-ivey-says-right-now-not-time-statewide-shelter-place-order/2922242001/|title=Coronavirus: Ivey says 'right now is not the time' for Alabama-wide shelter-in-place order|website=The Montgomery Advertiser|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Tuscaloosa extended its city-wide curfew to 24 hours, beginning March 29 at 10:00&nbsp;p.m., set to last an additional week. The Tuscaloosa stay-at-home order (the second in the state) came after [[Attorney General of Alabama|Alabama Attorney General]] [[Steve Marshall (politician)|Steve Marshall]]'s opinion published on the same day that provided cities and counties with more authority to combat the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/news/tuscaloosa/2020/03/maddox-extends-tuscaloosas-curfew-to-24-hours-citing-rapidly-developing-situation.html|title=Maddox extends Tuscaloosa's curfew to 24 hours, citing 'rapidly developing situation'|date=March 26, 2020|work=AL.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, all \"non-essential businesses\" in the state were ordered to be closed until April 17, including barbershops, furniture stores, gyms, casinos, theaters, arcades, night clubs, salons and spas. [[Alcoholic beverage control state|ABC stores]] would remain open. Governor Ivey again refused to issue a state-wide shelter-in-place order, saying \"I have the responsibility to look statewide and in this case, one size does not fit all\" and that she has to \"keep an eye on the economy\"; she added that she would not object to county and city-level containment efforts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/all-non-essential-businesses-closed-statewide-ivey-doesnt-issue-shelter-in-place.html|title=All 'non-essential businesses' closed statewide until April 17; Ivey doesn't issue shelter-in-place|date=March 27, 2020|work=AL.com}}</ref> [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]] mayor [[Steven Reed (mayor)|Steven Reed]] enacted an indefinite, 10:00&nbsp;p.m. to 5:00&nbsp;a.m. curfew starting the night of March 27 to help contain COVID-19. The order does not impact essential businesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/news/montgomery/2020/03/montgomery-mayor-enacts-indefinite-seven-hour-curfew-starting-10-pm-tonight.html|work=AL.com|title=Montgomery mayor enacts indefinite, seven-hour curfew starting 10 p.m. tonight|date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Alabama Department of Labor reported that from March 22\u201326, 59,783 Alabamians filed for [[Unemployment benefits|unemployment]], a five-fold growth over last week's 9,138 filings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/business/2020/03/alabama-unemployment-claims-surge-to-60000-this-week-as-coronavirus-creates-economic-havoc.html|title=Alabama unemployment claims surge to 60,000 this week as coronavirus creates economic havoc|date=March 27, 2020|work=AL.com}}</ref> Meanwhile, Archbishop [[Thomas John Rodi]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mobile|Archdiocese of Mobile]] and Bishop [[Robert Joseph Baker]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Birmingham in Alabama|Diocese of Birmingham]] continued the suspension of public [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Mass]] in Alabama through April 18, meaning no Easter Sunday Mass on April 12, in what Rodi called a \"painful decision\". Baker and Rodi initially issued the suspension of public Mass on March 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/coronavirus/2020/03/archbishop-rodi-calls-off-public-mass-for-easter-in-south-alabama.html|title=Bishops call off public Mass for Easter in Alabama|date=March 27, 2020|work=AL.com}}</ref>\n\n==== March 28&ndash;29 ====\nBy the end of March 28, there were 720 confirmed COVID-19 cases in Alabama.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.waaytv.com/content/news/Alabama-coronavirus-spread-on-similar-pace-with-Tennessee-Louisiana-based-on-last-three-days-569198611.html|title=Alabama coronavirus spread on similar pace with Tennessee, Louisiana based on last three days|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=WAAYTV}}</ref> Although the confirmed state death count was three at the time, [[Lee County, Alabama|Lee County]] Coroner Bill Harris said that of the around 19 COVID-19 patients at the [[List of hospitals in Alabama|East Alabama Medical Center]] in [[Opelika, Alabama|Opelika]], five had died between the morning of March 27 and 3:15&nbsp;p.m. on March 28. Two of the deaths were Lee County residents and three were residents from [[Chambers County, Alabama|Chambers County]], Harris said.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/news/montgomery/2020/03/coronavirus-kills-5-people-in-lee-county-in-1-day-coroner-says.html|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|title=Coronavirus kills 5 people in Lee County in 1 day, coroner says|work=AL.com}}</ref> Meanwhile, by March 28, the virus was confirmed in at least six [[Nursing home care|nursing homes]] in the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-confirmed-in-six-alabama-nursing-homes.html|title=Coronavirus confirmed in six Alabama nursing homes|work=AL.com|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nGovernor Ivey announced that [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] donated 63,000 [[N95 mask]]s for Alabama healthcare providers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus supplies: Apple donates 63,000 N-95 masks to Alabama|work=AL.com|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-supplies-apple-donates-63000-n-95-masks-to-alabama.html|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 5:30&nbsp;p.m. on March 29, Alabama had 827 confirmed cases while the death toll reached at least 10 after the East Alabama Medical Center announced its sixth fatality in three days, although the official count provided by ADPH was only 4 deaths. By this time the EAMC was the only hospital in the state to announce a COVID-19 death. The [[Mobile County, Alabama|Mobile County]] Health Department also recorded a death not yet reflected by ADPH numbers.<ref>{{cite news|work=AL.com|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/death-toll-from-coronavirus-rises-in-auburn-area-alabama-now-at-10-deaths.html|title=Death toll from coronavirus rises in Auburn area, Alabama now has at least 10 deaths|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Residents in the Opelika area were holding a \"Park and [[Prayer|Pray]]\" service twice daily in support of the hospital staff at the EAMC.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://yellowhammernews.com/community-holds-park-and-pray-twice-daily-at-east-alabama-medical-center-god-is-in-this/|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020|work=Yellowhammer News|title=Community holds 'Park and Pray' twice daily at East Alabama Medical Center \u2014 'God is in this'}}</ref> A similar scene was observed in the [[DCH Regional Medical Center]] parking lot in Tuscaloosa where a local church organized a worship service there.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbs42.com/news/local/church-gathers-to-worship-outside-dch-regional-medical-center-in-tuscaloosa/|title=Church gathers to worship outside DCH Regional Medical Center in Tuscaloosa|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020|work=Fox 6 WBRC}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n\n==== April 1&ndash;2 ====\nOn April 1, COVID-19 cases in Alabama reached 1,000 cases, according to the ADPH. 24 total deaths were reported with 17 confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.alabamanews.net/2020/04/01/covid-19-cases-in-alabama-hit-1000/|title=COVID-19 Cases in Alabama Hit 1,000|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|work=Alabama News}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, by 9:00&nbsp;pm, confirmed statewide cases rose to 1,270 out of 8,619 people thus far tested, with 17 confirmed deaths and 32 reported deaths statewide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abc3340.com/news/local/covid-19-in-alabama-news-summary-thursday-april-2-2020|title=COVID-19 in Alabama news summary|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|work=ABC 3340}}</ref>\n\nAlabama was projected to have the fourth-highest rate of COVID-19 fatalities in the nation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abc3340.com/news/local/alabama-projected-to-have-fourth-highest-rate-of-covid-19-fatalities-in-nation|title=Alabama projected to have fourth highest rate of COVID-19 fatalities in nation|work=ABC 3340|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Despite this projection, Governor Kay Ivey continued to resist demands to issue a state-wide shelter-in-place order but issued her fifth Supplemental State of Emergency (the third was on March 23 and the fourth was on March 27) to reduce [[red tape]] for healthcare providers, including allowing certified registered nurse practitioners, nurse midwives, physician assistants and anesthesia assistants to practice in a licensed health care facility. She also ordered the state board to adopt emergency rules to allow expedited reinstatement of medical licenses; moved to expand capacity of health care facilities; and moved to allow local jails release [[probation]] or [[parole]] violators who have been in custody for more than 20 days without a hearing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abc3340.com/news/local/gov-ivey-issues-supplemental-state-of-emergency-to-cut-red-tape-for-healthcare-providers|title=Gov. Ivey issues Supplemental State of Emergency to cut red tape for healthcare providers|work=ABC 3340|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that everyday since March 23, the ADPH was sharing a list of addresses of confirmed COVID-19 patients with the Alabama 911 Board to disseminate to local 911 response districts, reportedly to protect [[first responders]] from becoming infected&ndash;a possible breach of [[Privacy law|patient confidentiality law]]. [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] was the only other state known to be doing this at the time. The 911 Board said the policy was implemented after numerous state agencies expressed concerns about protecting first responders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/04/alabama-sharing-addresses-of-coronavirus-patients-with-911-responders.html|work=AL.com|title=Alabama sharing addresses of coronavirus patients with 911 responders|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== April 3&ndash;4 ====\n\nOn April 3, Governor Ivey issued a statewide stay-at-home order effective April 4 until April 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stay-at-home order issued for Alabama: What you can and can\u2019t do|first=Leada|last=Gore|work=[[al.com]]|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/04/stay-at-home-order-issued-for-alabama-what-you-can-and-cant-do.html}}</ref> [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] issued a stay-at-home order effective April 4 until April 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayor Stimpson announces stay-at-home order for Mobile|first=Leslie|last=Acosta|publisher=[[WEAR-TV]]|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|url=https://weartv.com/news/local/mayor-stimpson-announces-stay-at-home-order-for-mobile-04-03-2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery County]] authorities say they received 5,880 [[surgical mask]]s from the national stockpile with a 2010 expiration date had [[dry rot]] and were useless.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/491015-alabama-county-received-5000-rotted-masks-from-national-stockpile Alabama county received 5,000 rotted masks from national stockpile] BY KAELAN DEESE, The Hill, 3 Apr 2020</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[2021 World Games]] in Birmingham, originally scheduled for July 15\u201325, 2021, was postponed to July 7\u201317, 2022.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abc3340.com/news/local/world-games-rescheduled-to-july-2022|work=ABC 3340|title=World Games in Birmingham rescheduled to July 2022|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Alabama Crimson Tide football]] head coach [[Nick Saban]] and his Nick's Kids Foundation donated to food banks, contributed to the [[2-1-1|211]] program, provided lunches to [[DCH Regional Medical Center]] workers, and filmed [[Public service announcement|PSA]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2020/04/how-nick-saban-views-his-role-helping-during-coronavirus-crisis.html|title=How Nick Saban views his role helping during coronavirus crisis|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|work=AL.com}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on events==\nOn March 22, [[MOBICON|Mobicon]],  an annual fan convention held in [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] announced that the 2020 iteration of the convention scheduled for the last weekend of May had been postponed in response to the coronavirus pandemic.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe following table shows the number of cases in each county in Alabama.  The table can be sorted by clicking on the column heading to see, for example, how the number of cases varies with population density (people per square mile), or to see which counties have the most \ncases per capita (cases per person times 100,000).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"6\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alabama by County<ref name=\":0\" />\nUpdated April 5, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed<br /> Cases\n! scope=\"col\" |[[List of counties in Alabama|Population]] \n! scope=\"col\" |Cases per 100,000 <br /> people in county\n! scope=\"col\" |[[List of counties in Alabama|Area in<br />square miles]]\n! scope=\"col\" |[[List of counties in Alabama|Density in<br />people/sq mi]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Autauga County, Alabama|Autauga]]\n|12\n|54,571\n|22\n|594.4\n|92\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Baldwin County, Alabama|Baldwin]]\n|33\n|182,265\n|18\n|1,589.8\n|115\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Barbour County, Alabama|Barbour]]\n|2\n|27,457\n|7\n|884.9\n|31\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bibb County, Alabama|Bibb]]\n|6\n|22,915\n|26\n|622.6\n|37\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Blount County, Alabama|Blount]]\n|10\n|57,322\n|17\n|644.8\n|89\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bullock County, Alabama|Bullock]]\n|2\n|10,914\n|18\n|622.8\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Butler County, Alabama|Butler]]\n|1\n|20,947\n|5\n|776.8\n|27\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Calhoun County, Alabama|Calhoun]]\n|24\n|118,572\n|20\n|605.9\n|196\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Chambers County, Alabama|Chambers]]\n|90\n|34,215\n|263\n|596.5\n|57\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Cherokee County, Alabama|Cherokee]]\n|6\n|25,989\n|23\n|553.7\n|47\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Chilton County, Alabama|Chilton]]\